Terrible customer service. I had made a pick up order and about 10 minutes after pick up I returned because what I ordered was not what I recieved. I ordered a well done chopped steak but was given a chopped up hamburger that did not appear to be well done. When I tried to ask the manager for a different order to get a steak, he said thats what a chopped steak is and that they are closing up (this is 2 hours before they have advertised that they would be closing but you now things can happen where you close early). Anyway, he immediately walked away from me. I tried to talk to him for a refund because I can understand if they will not be cooking anything more because they may have cleaned the kitchen or had started to do so. He shows me the menu and just said you said chopped steak and thats how we make it so it is not his fault that I didnt understand. As I proceeded to explain to him a hamburger is not a steak, so I couldn't have known that he turned his back to me and started doing something else other than providing the customer his full attention. I had to call his attention back. He said he couldnt do anything and walked away. I was not given a refund nor any sort of remedy to the situation. It is absolutely ridiculous the lack of respect for a customer that I experienced. I can understand and let go the closing up and cleaning as an excuse for no refund or new order being made, however, the fact he attempted to ignore my complaint in the manner he did prompted me to write this review and warn other people incase they have an issue with a take out order being incorrect that this could happen.

I can expect nothing more from 5th avenue Diner but I could expect a great deal less, which is to say, this place can really come in clutch and not disappoint. In my case, it was 12:30am, in Bed-Stuy, and I really wanted a milkshake. 5th is the only 24 hour place with that service for miles around, so I decided to go way out of my way to give it a shot. I walked over a mile, waited 30 minutes for the train, took the 20-30 ride, and finally got a milkshake (that's not that impressive, but I had work early the next morning). To my delight, at 1:00am on a Thursday, a variety of parties were enjoying meals; some loners, but some nice families with children as well. I got a vanilla milkshake, the only other option than chocolate. Was it amazing? No. A tasty milkshake? Yes. It was $4. That's hard to find these days anywhere. So no quality is not high, but I'll be damned if 5th Ave Diner doesnt pursue an honorable mission and do so pretty well.

I wish I'd noticed they have amaretto french toast on the menu ("challah bread dipped in rich amaretto batter"), though my gyro sandwich was tasty (if a ridiculous mess that wouldn't stay in my drunken hands).  The seasoned waffle fries are delicious, and they have ranch they're happy to serve you.  The regular fries are good too, though you should really just get the waffle ones.  The only problem is all the regret you'll feel the next day, you know, if you're like me and have such feelings after a calorically explosive day of debauchery.  Oh and the California omelette sucks as the "guacamole" is a travesty, so don't order that.
